sentence: Consumer shares were mixed ahead of the opening bell Tuesday.
In consumer stocks news, The Home Depot ( HD ), a home improvement retailer, reported Q3 results that beat the Street view on both EPS and total revenues and has reaffirmed full-year guidance.
The company reported Q3 EPS of $1.15, up from $0.95 a year ago and beating analyst estimates of $1.14.
Total revenues of $20.51 billion were up from $19.47 billion in Q3 2013 and topped analyst estimates of $20.46 billion.
Shares of HD were down $0.48, or 0.49%, at $97.55 in early pre-market trading within a 52-week range of $73.96 - $99.36.
And, Dick's Sporting Goods ( DKS ) reported Q3 earnings of $0.41 per share, a penny ahead of the analyst consensus on Capital IQ and up from $0.40 per share last year.
Sales increased 9% from year ago levels to $1.53 billion, in line with expectations.
Consolidated same store sales increased 1.1%, compared to the company's guidance of an approximate 1 to 3% increase.
Finally, Jacobs Engineering ( JEC ) late Monday reported mixed results for Q4 ended September 26, with above-estimate earnings and weaker-than-forecast revenues.
The technical professional services firm said non-GAAP net earnings were $116.5 million, or $0.88 per diluted share, a $0.01 beat compared to the Capital IQ consensus of $0.87.
JEC was steady at $47.23 in pre-market.
